A [Member of the Legislative Assembly](/Member_of_the_Legislative_Assembly) (MLA) is, fundamentally, a person elected to represent the interests of their constituents within a [legislative assembly](/Legislative_assembly). This designation is most commonly applied to representatives serving in the legislatures of [federated states](/Federated_state) or [autonomous regions](/Autonomous_region), but its usage extends to several national legislative bodies as well. It’s a title that signifies a seat at the table, a voice in the grand, often tedious, theatre of governance.

### Australia

In the vast expanse of [Australia](/Australia), the nomenclature for these elected officials can be as varied as the landscape. In the legislative bodies of [New South Wales](/New_South_Wales_Legislative_Assembly), [Queensland](/Legislative_Assembly_of_Queensland), and [Victoria](/Victorian_Legislative_Assembly), as well as the [South Australian House of Assembly](/South_Australian_House_of_Assembly) and the [Tasmanian House of Assembly](/Tasmanian_House_of_Assembly), members are typically styled as [Members of Parliament](/Member_of_parliament) (MPs), indicated by the suffix MP. There was a time, however, when these same states employed the suffixes MLA and MHA (Member of the House of Assembly) respectively. It's a subtle shift, a linguistic tango that can leave one wondering if the title carries more weight than the actual function.

Meanwhile, in [Western Australia](/Western_Australian_Legislative_Assembly), the [Northern Territory](/Northern_Territory_Legislative_Assembly), and the [Australian Capital Territory](/Australian_Capital_Territory_Legislative_Assembly), the title MLA is the preferred designation. Yet, even here, the suffix MP is frequently encountered, a testament to the enduring prevalence of the more general parliamentary title. When it comes to the federal level, members of the [Australian House of Representatives](/Australian_House_of_Representatives) are known as MPs, eschewing the more specific MHR. It’s a system that prioritizes clarity, or perhaps, obfuscation, depending on your perspective.

### Brazil

Across the equator, in [Brazil](/Brazil), the elected representatives of the 26 [federated units](/Federative_units_of_Brazil) are known as *deputados estaduais*—state deputies. This is in contrast to the federal legislative structure, which is [bicameral](/Bicameral), while the state legislatures themselves are resolutely [unicameral](/Unicameral). The legislative assembly of the [Federal District](/Federal_District_(Brazil)) carries a slightly different moniker: the Legislative Chamber (*Câmara Legislativa*), and its members are termed *deputados distritais*, or district deputies. It’s worth noting that members of the federal [Lower House](/Chamber_of_Deputies_of_Brazil) are also referred to as deputies, but specifically as *deputados federais*, or federal deputies. The distinction, while seemingly minor, underscores the layered nature of Brazilian governance.

### Canada

In the vastness of [Canada](/Canada), the terminology for elected officials is a tapestry woven with distinct threads. At the federal level, members of the [House of Commons of Canada](/House_of_Commons_of_Canada) are designated as [Members of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament_(Canada)) (MPs), while those in the [Senate](/Senate_of_Canada) are simply called senators. Both groups, mind you, are integral parts of the [Parliament of Canada](/Parliament_of_Canada) and are considered parliamentarians. However, when we descend to the provincial and territorial levels, the standard designation across all [provinces and territories](/Provinces_and_territories_of_Canada) is MLA, with a few notable exceptions that disrupt the uniformity.

In [Ontario](/Ontario), since 1938, these legislators have been known as [Members of Provincial Parliament](/Member_of_Provincial_Parliament_(Ontario)) (MPPs), a title that predates the current MLA standard. Before that, both MPP and MLA were in vogue. Then there's [Quebec](/Quebec), where, since 1968, their English-speaking counterparts are known as [Members of the National Assembly](/National_Assembly_of_Quebec) (MNAs). And in [Newfoundland and Labrador](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador), the designation is [Members of the House of Assembly](/Newfoundland_and_Labrador_House_of_Assembly) (MHAs).

This divergence means that while ten out of thirteen provinces and territories officially use "MLA," a significant portion of Canadians—over 62%—interact with their provincial legislators under a different title. This is largely due to Ontario's substantial population, meaning more Canadians refer to their representatives as MPPs than as MLAs. Even [Nova Scotia](/Nova_Scotia), which styles its legislature as the [House of Assembly](/Nova_Scotia_House_of_Assembly), much like Newfoundland and Labrador, still refers to its legislators as MLAs. It's a linguistic landscape where consistency is more of an aspiration than a reality.

### Falkland Islands

In the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands), members of the [Legislative Assembly of the Falkland Islands](/Legislative_Assembly_of_the_Falkland_Islands) bear the suffix MLA. This body replaced the [Legislative Council of the Falkland Islands](/Legislative_Council_of_the_Falkland_Islands) in 2009, a council that had been in existence since the 1840s. Consequently, it’s not uncommon for Members of the Legislative Assembly to still be referred to as [Councillors](/Councillor), a holdover from the previous structure.

### Hong Kong

The members of the [Legislative Council of Hong Kong](/Legislative_Council_of_Hong_Kong) are addressed as [Legco](/Legco) Councillors. It’s a title that reflects the unique political landscape of the region.

### India

In [India](/India), the term MLA is deeply embedded in the political fabric. Of the nation's 28 states and eight [Union Territories (UTs)](/States_and_Union_Territories_of_India), all 28 states and three UTs—[Delhi](/National_Capital_Territory_of_Delhi), [Puducherry](/Puducherry_(union_territory)), and [Jammu and Kashmir](/Jammu_and_Kashmir_(Union_Territory))—possess [legislative assemblies](/Vidhan_Sabha).

Any individual who meets the [qualifications](/Vidhan_Sabha) can be elected as an MLA through [universal adult suffrage](/Universal_adult_suffrage), with the electorate comprising all citizens aged 18 and above within that state or UT. Those who are elected or appointed to a [Legislative Assembly](/Legislative_Assembly) (known as a *Vidhan Sabha*) are designated as Members of the Legislative Assembly, or MLAs. Each legislative constituency within a State or UT is represented by a single MLA. The [Constitution of India](/Constitution_of_India) stipulates that the number of seats in a legislature must not exceed 500 and must be at least 60. However, an Act of Parliament can permit fewer than 60 seats, a provision utilized in [Goa](/Goa), [Sikkim](/Sikkim), [Mizoram](/Mizoram), and the UT of [Puducherry](/Puducherry_(union_territory)).

The number of MLAs varies considerably between States and UTs, influenced by factors such as population. [Uttar Pradesh](/Uttar_Pradesh) boasts the highest number with 403 MLAs, while Puducherry has the fewest at 30. In the context of [parliamentary democracy](/parliamentary_democracy), where some legislators also serve in the executive branch, it's not uncommon for an MLA to hold multiple roles: representing their constituency, serving as a cabinet minister overseeing a particular department, and potentially as the chief minister of the state.

### Malaysia

Within [Malaysia](/Malaysia), each state legislative assembly is composed of elected representatives drawn from single-member constituencies, chosen through the [first-past-the-post](/first-past-the-post) system during state elections. The party that secures a majority in each assembly forms the state government, with its leader assuming the role of chief minister. These state legislative assemblies operate as [unicameral](/Unicameral) bodies, distinct from the [bicameral](/Bicameral) [Parliament of Malaysia](/Parliament_of_Malaysia). The hereditary rulers or governors hold the authority to dissolve their respective state legislative assemblies, acting upon the advice of the chief minister. Following a dissolution, elections are mandated within a 60-day interim period. Typically, state elections are synchronized with federal parliamentary elections, with exceptions such as Sarawak, and prior to 2004, Sabah.

### Northern Ireland

In [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland), the members of the [Northern Ireland Assembly](/Northern_Ireland_Assembly), the [devolved](/Devolution) [legislature](/Legislature) for the region, are known as MLAs (Members of the Legislative Assembly). The Assembly experienced a period of suspension beginning on October 14, 2002. However, those elected in the [2003 Assembly Election](/2003_Northern_Ireland_Assembly_election) were convened on May 15, 2006, under the terms of the [Northern Ireland Act 2006](/Northern_Ireland_Act_2006). Their purpose was to elect a First Minister and deputy First Minister and to select members for an Executive before November 25, 2006, all as a prelude to the restoration of devolved government. A subsequent [election](/2007_Northern_Ireland_Assembly_election) was held on March 7, 2007, and devolved powers were reinstated to the Assembly in May 2007.

### South Korea

In [South Korea](/South_Korea), members of the various [provincial legislative assemblies](/Administrative_divisions_of_South_Korea) can be referred to as MLAs in English. It's a functional descriptor within the English-speaking context, even if the official Korean titles may differ.

### United States

Within the [United States of America](/United_States_of_America), the term "state legislator" serves as a broad descriptor for any member of the legislative body within one of the country's 50 [states](/U.S._state). The formal designation for these legislative bodies is not uniform; it varies significantly from state to state. In 24 states, the legislature is simply called the Legislature or the State Legislature. Nineteen states opt for the name General Assembly. Massachusetts and New Hampshire refer to their legislative bodies as the General Court, while North Dakota and Oregon designate theirs as the Legislative Assembly.

To mitigate potential confusion with their federal counterparts, the [Associated Press guidelines for journalists](/AP_Stylebook) recommend using the titles "state representative" or "state senator" when referring to state legislators. It’s a pragmatic approach to maintain clarity in a system with multiple layers of representation.

### Wales

In [Wales](/Wales), the members of the [Senedd](/Senedd), the [devolved](/Devolution) Parliament, are generally known as [MSs](/Members_of_the_Senedd) or *Aelodau o'r Senedd* (ASau). This designation reflects the unique status and evolution of the Welsh Parliament. The name change from the National Assembly for Wales to the Senedd Cymru, or Welsh Parliament, in 2020, also coincided with a shift in how its members are formally referred to.